the available values are @samp{chi2} (Chi-square test)@comma{} @samp{ks}
(Kolmogorov-Smirnov test)@comma{} @samp{kuiper} (Kuiper's test)@comma{}
@samp{cmv} (Cram@'er-Von Mises test)@comma{} @samp{ad} (Anderson-Darling
test)@comma{}
@samp{FL2} (L@math{^2}-norm on @math{F})@comma{}
@samp{FL2w} (weighted L@math{^2}-norm
on @math{F})@footnote{See [Quey and Renversade, CMAME, 2018].}@comma{}
@samp{FL2wu} (weighted L@math{^2}-norm
on @math{F} corresponding to @samp{FL2w} for a unimodal distribution)@comma{}
and the default value is @samp{FL2w}.
@*
@mybullet For @samp{@code{centroid}}@comma{} a Minkowski distance
between the seeds and centroids is used@comma{} and can be
@samp{@code{L1}}@comma{} @samp{@code{L2}} or @samp{@code{Linf}}.
@*
@mybullet For @samp{@code{tesr}}@comma{} the definition of the
objective function includes several factors.
First@comma{} preprocessing operations to the raster tessellation can be
applied using @samp{@code{transform(@var{operations})}}@comma{} where
@samp{@var{operations}} can include @samp{scale} to scale the tessellation to
correct for a global cell elongation or @samp{rasterscale} to scale the raster
itself to correct for a global voxel elongation (which may result from
operation @samp{scale}); combine with @samp{@SEPNODEP}.
Second@comma{} control points can be defined using
@samp{@code{pts(@var{args})}} where @samp{@code{args}} can include
@samp{region=@var{region}} where @samp{@var{region}} can be @samp{@code{surf}}
for surface voxels or @samp{@code{all}} for all voxels@comma{} and
@samp{res=@var{res}} where @samp{@var{res}} is the resolution@comma{}
i.e.@ the average number of control points along a direction of a grain;
combine with @samp{@SEPNODEP}.
Third@comma{} the expression of the objective function @i{per se} can be
specified using @samp{val(@var{expr})}@comma{} where @samp{@var{expr}} can be
@samp{bounddist} for minimizing the distance between the raster tessellation
and tessellation cell boundaries@comma{} or @samp{intervol} for maximizing
the volume intersection between the raster tessellation and tessellation
(both provide similar results).  To define the objective
function@comma{} combine the above factors using @samp{+}.
The default value is @samp{pts(region=surf,res=5)+val(bounddist)}.
It is finally possible to define how the different parts of
the objective function are combined into the objective function (in the case
where several properties are specified)@comma{}
using @samp{general:@var{objective_function}}@comma{} where
@samp{@var{objective_function}} can be @samp{L1}@comma{} @samp{L2} or
@samp{Linf}; the default is @samp{L2}.
,
any, default}

